.TH LSBIN "1" "December 2025" "lsbin 202211041334-git" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
lsbin \- Enhanced ls wrapper with convenient listing commands and color output
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B lsbin
[\fI\,OPTIONS\fR] [\fI\,COMMAND\fR] [\fI\,ARGUMENTS\fR]
.PP
.B lsbin
.BR l.
[\fI\,PATH\fR]
.PP
.B lsbin
.BR ls | la | ll | lla | dir
[\fI\,PATH\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B lsbin
is an enhanced wrapper around the standard ls command that provides convenient listing commands with automatic color output and predefined formatting options. It simplifies common directory listing tasks with easy-to-remember command aliases and consistent colored output across all operations.
.PP
The script simplifies file listing by providing short command aliases for common ls operations, automatic color output for all listing modes, consistent formatting across different views, dotfile filtering with l. command, long format listings with ll and lla commands, directory-only listings with dir command, and configurable color settings for terminal output.
.PP
lsbin is particularly useful for quick directory navigation and inspection, consistent file listing across different environments, simplified dotfile management and inspection, shell script integration for formatted listings, and automated file system exploration tasks.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.BR l.
List only dotfiles (files and directories starting with dot). Uses ls -hA and filters output with grep to show only entries beginning with a dot.
.TP
.BR ls
List files with human-readable sizes and show all files except . and ... Equivalent to: ls --color=auto -hA
.TP
.BR la
List all files including hidden files with human-readable sizes. Equivalent to: ls --color=auto -hA (same as ls command).
.TP
.BR ll
List files in long format with human-readable sizes (no hidden files). Equivalent to: ls --color=auto -hl
.TP
.BR lla
List all files in long format with human-readable sizes including hidden files. Equivalent to: ls --color=auto -hlA
.TP
.BR dir
List only directories with human-readable sizes. Equivalent to: ls --color=auto -hD
.TP
(default)
When no command specified, defaults to la behavior (list all files with human-readable sizes).
