.SH COLOR OUTPUT
How lsbin provides colored file listings:
.SS Automatic Coloring
.RS
.EX
# Color enabled by default
lsbin ls

# All commands use --color=auto
ls --color=auto <options>
.EE
.IP \(bu 2
Uses ls --color=auto for all operations
.IP \(bu 2
Respects LS_COLORS environment variable
.IP \(bu 2
Automatically detects terminal capabilities
.IP \(bu 2
Disables color for pipe/redirection
.RE
.SS Color Scheme
.RS
Typical color mappings (depends on LS_COLORS):
.IP \(bu 2
.B Directories:
Blue/Cyan
.IP \(bu 2
.B Executables:
Green
.IP \(bu 2
.B Symlinks:
Cyan
.IP \(bu 2
.B Archives:
Red
.IP \(bu 2
.B Images:
Magenta
.IP \(bu 2
.B Regular files:
Default terminal color
.RE
.SS Disable Colors
.RS
.EX
# Use --raw to disable color
lsbin --raw ls

# Or redirect output (automatic)
